Creating images with R

with a little bit of magick

Jaden Hazelwood

2023-03-12

My meme:

My meme follows the classical “Stacked image” meme format. I wanted something which documents how much I love the class Stats220 and its teaching form. I also wanted to create something that shows my anger with R’s indexing starting at one.

Hope you enjoy the meme as much as I do!

My code used to make the meme:

library (magick)

#Initialize height and width constants
DEFAULT_HEIGHT <- 175
DEFAULT_WIDTH <- 175

#Create a black box object to base text boxes for the meme

black_box <- image_blank(height = DEFAULT_HEIGHT,
                        width = DEFAULT_WIDTH,
                        color = "#000000")

#Making the text boxes from the black box object for our meme

text_box_one <- image_annotate(image = black_box,
                            text = "Studying python in \n Compsci 130",
                            color = "#FFFFFF",
                            size = 20,
                            font = "Impact",
                            gravity = "center")

text_box_two <- image_annotate(image = black_box,
                               text = "Studying Java in \n in Compsci 230",
                               color = "#FFFFFF",
                               size = 20,
                               font = "Impact",
                               gravity = "center")

text_box_three <- image_annotate(image = black_box,
                                 text = "Studying R in \n in Stats 220",
                                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                                 size = 20,
                                 font = "Impact",
                                 gravity = "center")

text_box_four <- image_annotate(image = black_box,
                                 text = "Finding out indexing \n starts at 1 in R",
                                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                                 size = 20,
                                 font = "Impact",
                                 gravity = "center")


#Loading in and scaling corresponding images

sad_cat_one <- image_read("https://i.pinimg.com/564x/98/fc/88/98fc8863c7e68df57cd7ad7442f0ec18.jpg") %>% 
  image_scale("175")

sad_cat_two <- image_read("https://i.pinimg.com/236x/61/c7/80/61c780b045f999daacfd85e6f5ee96c8.jpg") %>% 
  image_scale("175")


happy_cat <- image_read("C:\\Users\\Jaden Hazelwood\\Desktop\\Stats 220\\Project1\\Images\\happy_cat.jfif") %>% 
  image_scale("175")

angry_cat <- image_read("https://i.cbc.ca/1.5359228.1577206958!/fileImage/httpImage/smudge-the-viral-cat.jpg") %>% 
  image_scale("175")

#Creating vectors for text box and cats and appending the images into a stack

text_boxes_stacked <- c(text_box_one, 
                        text_box_two, 
                        text_box_three, 
                        text_box_four) %>% 
  image_append(stack = TRUE)

cat_images_stacked <- c(sad_cat_one, 
                        sad_cat_two, 
                        happy_cat, 
                        angry_cat) %>% 
  image_append(stack = TRUE)

#Creating the final meme by appending the two image stacks

meme_vector <- c(text_boxes_stacked, cat_images_stacked)

meme <- image_append(meme_vector, stack = FALSE)

#Creating a png for the meme to be distributed

meme %>% image_write(path = "meme.png", format = "png")

meme

My animation:

My animation uses pictures of my dog in order to progressively display my mood during a day at university, something which is universally relateable to students.

My code used to make the animation:

library(magick)

#Creating a vectors to index for animation quotes

animation_quotes_vector <- c("Me the night before uni", "Me getting ready for uni", "Me taking the bus to uni", "Me during lectures at uni", "Me recovering from uni")

#Creating images, scaling and annotating

animation_image_1 <- image_read("C:\\Users\\Jaden Hazelwood\\Desktop\\Stats 220\\Project1\\Images\\image_one.jpg")%>%
  image_scale("500")%>%
  image_annotate(text = animation_quotes_vector[1], 
                 size = 40,
                 gravity = "North",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 font = "Impact",
                 boxcolor = "#000000") 

animation_image_2 <- image_read("C:\\Users\\Jaden Hazelwood\\Desktop\\Stats 220\\Project1\\Images\\image_two.jpg")%>%
  image_scale("500")%>%
  image_annotate(text = animation_quotes_vector[2], 
                 size = 40,
                 gravity = "North",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 font = "Impact",
                 boxcolor = "#000000") 

animation_image_3 <- image_read("C:\\Users\\Jaden Hazelwood\\Desktop\\Stats 220\\Project1\\Images\\image_three.jpg")%>%
  image_scale("500")%>%
  image_annotate(text = animation_quotes_vector[3], 
                 size = 40,
                 gravity = "North",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 font = "Impact",
                 boxcolor = "#000000") 

animation_image_4 <- image_read("C:\\Users\\Jaden Hazelwood\\Desktop\\Stats 220\\Project1\\Images\\image_four.jpg")%>%
  image_scale("500")%>%
  image_annotate(text = animation_quotes_vector[4], 
                 size = 40,
                 gravity = "North",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 font = "Impact",
                 boxcolor = "#000000") 

animation_image_5 <- image_read("C:\\Users\\Jaden Hazelwood\\Desktop\\Stats 220\\Project1\\Images\\image_five.jpg")%>%
  image_scale("500")%>%
  image_annotate(text = animation_quotes_vector[5], 
                 size = 40,
                 gravity = "North",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 font = "Impact",
                 boxcolor = "#000000") 

#Creating a frames vector for animation

frames_vector <- c(animation_image_1, animation_image_2, animation_image_3, animation_image_4, animation_image_5)

#Creating the final animation

animation <- image_animate(frames_vector, fps = 1)%>%
  image_write("my_animation.gif")
